iversity Press]]\n | isbn = 978-0-8135-3191-5\n | url = https://archive.org/details/cinematicimagina0000vird\n | url-access = registration\n | ref = harv\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book\n | surname1 = Chopra\n | given1 = Aditya\n | surname2 = Kabir\n | given2 = Nasreen Munni\n | date = 12 December 2014\n | title = Aditya Chopra Relives&nbsp;... (Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge: As Told to Nasreen Munni Kabir)\n | publisher = [[Yash Raj Films]]\n | isbn = 978-93-5196-188-8\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n | surname1= Sharpe\n | first1= Jenny\n | title= Gender, Nation, and Globalization in ''Monsoon Wedding'' and ''Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge''\n | journal= Meridians: Feminism, Race, Transnationalism\n | volume = 6\n | issue = 1\n | year = 2005\n | pages = 58\u201381\n | doi= 10.1353/mer.2005.0032}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Film|Bollywood|1990s|India}}\n* [https://www.yashrajfilms.com/movies/dilwale-dulhania-le-jayenge ''Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge'' Official Site]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0112870}}\n* [http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b7e63fe2b ''Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge''] at the [[British Film Institute]]'s Film and TV Database <!-- cannot find correct ID so doing manually for now * {{Bfidb title|id=4ce2b7e63fe2b|title=Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge}} -->\n* {{Tcmdb title|439077|Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge}}\n* {{AllRovi movie|id=289660|title=Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/dilwale-dulhania-le-jayenge/ ''Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge''] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n\n{{FilmfareAwardBestFilm 1991\u20132010}}\n{{National Film Award Wholesome Entertainment}}\n{{ScreenAwardBestFilm}}\n{{Yash Raj Films}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films about Indian weddings]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jatin\u2013Lalit]]\n[[Category:Films set in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Yash Raj Films films]]\n[[Category:Hindi films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:1995 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "117.192.121.231", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dilwale_Dulhania_Le_Jayenge"}
{"title_page": "Ran Ronen-Pekker", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli Air Force general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = '''Ran Ronen-Pekker'''\n| image         = Ran-pakar.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1936|7|19}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2016|12|3|1936|7|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kfar Vitkin]], [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate for Palestine]]\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Israel}}\n| branch        = {{air force|Israel}}\n| serviceyears  = 1954\u20131980\n| rank          = [[Brigadier General]]\n| commands      = 119 Squadron<br />One Squadron<br />IAF Flight School<br />[[Tel Nof Airbase]]\n| battles       = [[Suez Crisis|Sinai Campaign]]<br />[[Six-Day War]]<br />[[War of Attrition]]<br />[[Yom Kippur War]]\n| awards        = \n| laterwork     = Consul General to Los Angeles<br />Zahala<br />Pekker Enterprises<br />[[Israel Aerospace Industries]]\n}}\n'''Ran Ronen''' (originally '''Ran Pekker''')  was an [[Flying ace|ace]] fighter pilot and commander in the [[Israeli Air Force|Israeli Air Force (IAF)]], credited with seven kills. He commanded various fighter squadrons, the [[Israeli Air Force Flight Academy|IAF flight academy]], and the [[Tel Nof Airbase]], retiring from the IAF with the rank of [[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]]. One of his pilots later described him as \"the greatest squadron commander ever\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/246 246]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/246}}</ref>\n\n==Biography and early military service==\nRan Ronen was born on 19 July 1936 in [[Kfar Vitkin]], to Leah (nee Sturman) and David Pekker, founding members of Kfar Vitkin.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5020347|title=Ran Peker's Political and Business Connections|date=2008-08-31|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-01-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1954 he enlisted in the IAF. He began flying  [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] aircraft and later served in the [[117 Squadron (Israel)|117th Squadron]] flying [[Gloster Meteor|Meteor]]<nowiki/>s.  He later joined the new 113th Squadron, flying [[Dassault Ouragan|Ouragan]]s. During the [[Suez Crisis|Sinai Campaign]], he flew the new French [[Dassault Myst\u00e8re|Myst\u00e8re]]. After the war, he spent a year in a French Air Force squadron as part of a training mission for IAF pilots,<ref name=\":5\" /> served as an instructor in the Air Force flight school, and in 1962 was appointed deputy commander of the [[101 Squadron (Israel)|101st squadron.]]\n\n==Pre\u2013Six-Day War activities==\n===Mirage incident===\nIn 1963, Ronen was Flying a new [[Dassault Mirage III|Mirage III]], when his engine lost power. He did not want to eject and risk killing people in a village below, but he remembered the warning from the French manufacturers that should he attempt to land without power, the nose of the plane would slam against the ground, killing the pilot. He guided the plane until he was over an empty field and finally ejected at an altitude of only 500 feet. The plane glided down and landed nearly intact. An inspection revealed the issue to be a weak fuel pump component which explained the failure and previous crashes of 7 IAF and 16 French Mirages. [[Ezer Weizman]], then the Israeli Air Force Commander, sent him a bottle of whiskey and a poem praising the unique pilot who landed his plane after ejecting. Ronen continued using the plane after its repairs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.walla.co.il/item/3021030/|title=The Story of Reservist Brigadier General Ran Pekker|last=|first=|date=|work=Walla|access-date=|language=Hebrew}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/190 190]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/190}}</ref>\n\nAfter a period at the IAF Officer School he was appointed deputy commander of a combat squadron at [[Hatzor Airbase]], and in the summer of 1965 was appointed the commander of the [[119 Squadron (Israel)|119 \"bat\" Mirage Squadron]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iaf.org.il/625-19934-he/IAF.aspx|title=\u05d0\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d7\u05d9\u05dc-\u05d4\u05d0\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05e8|publisher=Israel Air Force|language=Hebrew|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Saying-good-bye-to-Ran-Pekker-the-legendary-IAF-combat-pilot-474450|title=Saying good-bye to Ran Pekker, the legendary IAF combat pilot|last=|first=|date=|work=The Jerusalem Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 August 1966, Ronen escorted Iraqi pilot [[Munir Redfa]], who defected together with his [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21]] in [[Operation Diamond]].\n\nOn 13 November 1966, during [[Samu incident|Operation Shredder]], he achieved his first air to air kill, shooting down a Jordanian [[Hawker Hunter]] after an eight-minute [[dogfight]] \u2013 the longest dogfight in IAF history.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/220 220]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/220}}</ref> On 7 April 1967, he downed a Syrian MiG-21.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n==Six-Day War==\nDuring the [[Six-Day War|1967 Six-Day War]], Ronen's squadron took part in [[Operation Focus|Operation Moked]] and other bombing missions, as well as air to air battles against Syrian and Egyptian pilots. Ronen shot down two Egyptian [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-19|MiG-19s]] for a squadron total of 19 kills and two aircraft lost, less than any other squadron. None of their pilots were killed.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==War of Attrition and Yom Kippur War==\nDuring the [[War of Attrition]], Ronen commanded the IAF Flight School while still flying reserve in Squadron 119.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://aviationbookreviews.com/134th-review-eagle-in-the-sky-ran-ronen-pekker|title=134th review Eagle in the Sky- Ran Ronen (Pekker)}}</ref> He shot down three Egyptian MiG-21s, making him Israel\u2019s second jet ace with a total of seven kills.\n\nIn the summer of 1970, after Shmuel Hetz, commander of Phantom [[201 Squadron (Israel)|Squadron 201]] was shot down, Ronen was appointed the commander of the squadron, despite having never flown the [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom]] before.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/298 298]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/298}}</ref> Ronen led the squadron in assaults against the Egyptian [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] system and is credited with restoring the fighting spirit of the squadron.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1972 After completing a command course at [[Marine Corps Base Quantico]], he was appointed commander of the IAF Training division and promoted to the rank of [[colonel]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nHe was appointed the commander of the Tel Nof Airbase and commanded it during the [[Yom Kippur War]]. In 1975 he was promoted to brigadier general.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 1979 he returned to Israel from two years at [[Harvard University]]<ref name=\":5\" /> and was considered for the post of commander of the air force.\n\nHowever anonymous reports reached the Defense Minister, alleging that immediately after the Six-Day War, Ronen executed a captured Jordanian company commander who had confessed to murdering Israeli pilot Shabtai Ben-Aharon, who had bailed out near [[Ma'ale Adumim|Ma'aleh Adumim]]. Ronen decried it as libel.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.makorrishon.co.il/nrg/online/archive/ART/260/286.html|title=\u05e2\u05e9\u05d9\u05ea\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05d5\u05df \u05e9\u05d2\u05d9\u05d0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05d7\u05d9\u05d9 \u05d5\u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d2\u05d0\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d0\u05ea \u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05df \u05ea\u05d9\u05d7\u05e7\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9 \u05e2\u05dd \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9|last=|first=|date=|work=Maariv|access-date=|language=Hebrew}}</ref> Several investigations cleared Ronen of this accusation, but the [[Military Advocate General]]  recommended to the chief of staff to reconsider Ronen\u2019s promotion. This, as well as a personal feud between Ronen and IAF commander General [[David Ivry]], resulted in Ronen being denied promotion.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn November 1981 Ronen retired from the IDF with the rank of brigadier general having flown over 350 combat sorties.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/135628|title=Moskowitz Prize for Zionism 2010|last=|first=|date=|work=Arutz Sheva|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Air to air victories==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Number'''\n|'''Date'''\n|'''Ronen's plane'''\n|'''Enemy plane'''\n|'''Weapon used''' \n|'''Details'''\n|-\n|1\n|13 November 1966\n|Mirage III\n|Jordanian Hawker Hunter\n|Cannon\n|In the IAF's longest dogfight ever, against [[Muwaffaq Salti]], the commander of the Jordanian Hunter Squadron\n|-\n|2\n|7 April 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Syrian MiG-21\n|Cannon\n|During a mass air battle over the [[Golan Heights]]\n|-\n|3\n|5 June 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-19\n|Cannon\n|Over Ghardaka, Part of Operation Moked\n|-\n|4\n|5 June 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-19\n|Cannon\n|Second kill of the same battle\n|-\n|5\n|5 June 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-21\n|[[Shafrir-2]]\n|During a mass air battle over the [[Nile Delta]]\n|-\n|6\n|21 May 1969\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-21\n|Cannon\n|Over [[Ismailia|Ismailla]]\n|-\n|7\n|11 September 1969\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-21\n|[[AIM-9 Sidewinder|Sidewinder]]\n|During a mass air battle over the [[Nile Delta]]\n|}\n\n==After his retirement from the IDF==\nRonen worked as deputy director of the advertising agency Dahaf.\n\nIn 1989 he was appointed Consul General of Israel in Los Angeles and Hebraized his surname to Ronen. He served for three years.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 1992 he founded the Zahala Project, which works with at-risk teenagers to instill the values of Zionism and social responsibility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aluma.org.il/program/yedidut-zahala/|title=Yedidut Zahala {{!}} \u05d0\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05d4|website=aluma.org.il|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref> The project was adopted by the Ministry of Education, and defined by Education Minister [[Zevulun Hammer]] as a \"national project\". For his work with Zahala, Ronen (along with Ruth Dayan) was awarded the Yigal Alon Prize. His mentor and former commander Ezer Weizman was honored with giving him the award.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2002 he published his autobiography ''Eagle in the Sky'' in Hebrew. An English version was released in 2016 with a foreword by [[Dan Halutz]], a former commander of the IAF.\n\nIn 2007 he was featured in two episodes of the History Channel's ''[[Dogfights (TV series)|Dogfights]]''. In \"Dogfights of the Middle East\" Ronen covers the battle of Ghardaka and the defection of an Iraqi MiG-21, and in \"Desert Aces\" he relates his downing of the Jordanian Hawker Hunter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearethemighty.com/articles/israel-recently-buried-ran-ronen-an-ace-few-ever-heard-of|title=Israel recently buried Ran Ronen, an ace few ever heard of|date=2017-01-16|website=We Are The Mighty|language=en|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he won the [[Moskowitz Prize for Zionism]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moskowitzprize.com/en/award-winners/2008-winners/ran-pecker-ronen|title=Award winners 2008 Ran Pecker Ronen}}</ref> The award committee explained the decision to honor Ronen \"The prize is awarded for being an exemplary example of courage, sacrifice and leadership, for his exceptional handling of the educational and ethical challenges facing Zionism, and for his success in establishing the Zahala project, by recruiting former officers and commanders to the forefront of social action for Israeli youth.\"\n\nRonen was the sole owner of Pekker Enterprises, an advisory firm.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nFrom 2009 to 2012 he was a member of the Board of Directors of [[Israel Aerospace Industries]].\n\nIn 2013 his book ''Diary of Operations'' was published by ''[[Yedioth Ahronoth]]''. It is based on his previous book, but focuses on the operational issues.\n\n==Academic achievements==\nHe held a Master's degree in Public Administration from Harvard University and served as a Research Fellow at the [[Brookings Institution]] and at the [[RAND Corporation]].\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Ran Pecker memorial in Herzliya.jpg|thumb|Memorial to Ran Ronen at a [[roundabout]] in [[Herzliya]]]]\nAt the age of 21, Ronen married Herutah,<ref name=\":7\" /> whom he met at the age of eight, and the couple had three children.  After thirty years of marriage, the couple divorced.  His second wife was singer Mali Bronstein, whom he later divorced.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nRan Ronen died of blood cancer on December 3, 2016.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Muwaffaq Salti Air Base]]\n* [[List of Israeli flying aces]]\n* [[Giora Romm]]\n* [[Giora Epstein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mRoK3hLHvrk Moskowitz Prize 2008 on youtube]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0950883/?ref_=ttep_ep11 ''Dogfights of the Middle east'' on IMDb]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1084220/?ref_=ttep_ep5 ''Deserts Aces'' on IMDb]\n* [http://www.iaf.org.il/4451-47021-en/IAF.aspx Ran Ronen on the IAF website]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/keyword/ran-ronen Articles in the LA times about Ran Ronen]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ronen-Pekker, Ran}}\n[[Category:Israeli flying aces]]\n[[Category:Israeli Air Force generals]]\n[[Category:Israeli diplomats]]\n[[Category:RAND Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Brookings Institution]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moskowitz Prize for Zionism laureates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli Air Force general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = '''Ran Ronen-Pekker'''\n| image         = Ran-pakar.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1936|7|19}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2016|12|3|1936|7|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kfar Vitkin]], [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate for Palestine]]\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Israel}}\n| branch        = {{air force|Israel}}\n| serviceyears  = 1954\u20131980\n| rank          = [[Brigadier General]]\n| commands      = 119 Squadron<br />One Squadron<br />IAF Flight School<br />[[Tel Nof Airbase]]\n| battles       = [[Suez Crisis|Sinai Campaign]]<br />[[Six-Day War]]<br />[[War of Attrition]]<br />[[Yom Kippur War]]\n| awards        = \n| laterwork     = Consul General to Los Angeles<br />Zahala<br />Pekker Enterprises<br />[[Israel Aerospace Industries]]\n}}\n'''Ran Ronen''' (originally '''Ran Pekker''')  was an [[Flying ace|ace]] fighter pilot and commander in the [[Israeli Air Force|Israeli Air Force (IAF)]], credited with seven kills. He commanded various fighter squadrons, the [[Israeli Air Force Flight Academy|IAF flight academy]], and the [[Tel Nof Airbase]], retiring from the IAF with the rank of [[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]]. One of his pilots later described him as \"the greatest squadron commander ever\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/246 246]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/246}}</ref>\n\n==Biography and early military service==\nRan Ronen was born on 19 July 1936 in [[Kfar Vitkin]], to Leah (nee Sturman) and David Pekker, founding members of Kfar Vitkin.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5020347|title=Ran Peker's Political and Business Connections|date=2008-08-31|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-01-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1954 he enlisted in the IAF. He began flying  [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] aircraft and later served in the [[117 Squadron (Israel)|117th Squadron]] flying [[Gloster Meteor|Meteor]]<nowiki/>s.  He later joined the new 113th Squadron, flying [[Dassault Ouragan|Ouragan]]s. During the [[Suez Crisis|Sinai Campaign]], he flew the new French [[Dassault Myst\u00e8re|Myst\u00e8re]]. After the war, he spent a year in a French Air Force squadron as part of a training mission for IAF pilots,<ref name=\":5\" /> served as an instructor in the Air Force flight school, and in 1962 was appointed deputy commander of the [[101 Squadron (Israel)|101st squadron.]]\n\n==Pre\u2013Six-Day War activities==\n===Mirage incident===\nIn 1963, Ronen was Flying a new [[Dassault Mirage III|Mirage III]], when his engine lost power. He did not want to eject and risk killing people in a village below, but he remembered the warning from the French manufacturers that should he attempt to land without power, the nose of the plane would slam against the ground, killing the pilot. He guided the plane until he was over an empty field and finally ejected at an altitude of only 500 feet. The plane glided down and landed nearly intact. An inspection revealed the issue to be a weak fuel pump component which explained the failure and previous crashes of 7 IAF and 16 French Mirages. [[Ezer Weizman]], then the Israeli Air Force Commander, sent him a bottle of whiskey and a poem praising the unique pilot who landed his plane after ejecting. Ronen continued using the plane after its repairs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.walla.co.il/item/3021030/|title=The Story of Reservist Brigadier General Ran Pekker|last=|first=|date=|work=Walla|access-date=|language=Hebrew}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/190 190]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/190}}</ref>\n\nAfter a period at the IAF Officer School he was appointed deputy commander of a combat squadron at [[Hatzor Airbase]], and in the summer of 1965 was appointed the commander of the [[119 Squadron (Israel)|119 \"bat\" Mirage Squadron]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iaf.org.il/625-19934-he/IAF.aspx|title=\u05d0\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d7\u05d9\u05dc-\u05d4\u05d0\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05e8|publisher=Israel Air Force|language=Hebrew|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Saying-good-bye-to-Ran-Pekker-the-legendary-IAF-combat-pilot-474450|title=Saying good-bye to Ran Pekker, the legendary IAF combat pilot|last=|first=|date=|work=The Jerusalem Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 August 1966, Ronen escorted Iraqi pilot [[Munir Redfa]], who defected together with his [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21]] in [[Operation Diamond]].\n\nOn 13 November 1966, during [[Samu incident|Operation Shredder]], he achieved his first air to air kill, shooting down a Jordanian [[Hawker Hunter]] after an eight-minute [[dogfight]] \u2013 the longest dogfight in IAF history.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/220 220]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/220}}</ref> On 7 April 1967, he downed a Syrian MiG-21.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n==Six-Day War==\nDuring the [[Six-Day War|1967 Six-Day War]], Ronen's squadron took part in [[Operation Focus|Operation Moked]] and other bombing missions, as well as air to air battles against Syrian and Egyptian pilots. Ronen shot down two Egyptian [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-19|MiG-19s]] for a squadron total of 19 kills and two aircraft lost, less than any other squadron. None of their pilots were killed.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==War of Attrition and Yom Kippur War==\nDuring the [[War of Attrition]], Ronen commanded the IAF Flight School while still flying reserve in Squadron 119.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://aviationbookreviews.com/134th-review-eagle-in-the-sky-ran-ronen-pekker|title=134th review Eagle in the Sky- Ran Ronen (Pekker)}}</ref> He shot down three Egyptian MiG-21s, making him Israel\u2019s second jet ace with a total of seven kills.\n\nIn the summer of 1970, after Shmuel Hetz, commander of Phantom [[201 Squadron (Israel)|Squadron 201]] was shot down, Ronen was appointed the commander of the squadron, despite having never flown the [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom]] before.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=No Margin for Error: The Making of The Israeli Air Force|last=Yonay|first=Ehud|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=1993|isbn=0-679-41563-7|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/298 298]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780679415633/page/298}}</ref> Ronen led the squadron in assaults against the Egyptian [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] system and is credited with restoring the fighting spirit of the squadron.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1972 After completing a command course at [[Marine Corps Base Quantico]], he was appointed commander of the IAF Training division and promoted to the rank of [[colonel]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nHe was appointed the commander of the Tel Nof Airbase and commanded it during the [[Yom Kippur War]]. In 1975 he was promoted to brigadier general.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 1979 he returned to Israel from two years at [[Harvard University]]<ref name=\":5\" /> and was considered for the post of commander of the air force.\n\nHowever anonymous reports reached the Defense Minister, alleging that immediately after the Six-Day War, Ronen executed a captured Jordanian company commander who had confessed to murdering Israeli pilot Shabtai Ben-Aharon, who had bailed out near [[Ma'ale Adumim|Ma'aleh Adumim]]. Ronen decried it as libel.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.makorrishon.co.il/nrg/online/archive/ART/260/286.html|title=\u05e2\u05e9\u05d9\u05ea\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05d5\u05df \u05e9\u05d2\u05d9\u05d0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05d7\u05d9\u05d9 \u05d5\u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d2\u05d0\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d0\u05ea \u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05df \u05ea\u05d9\u05d7\u05e7\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9 \u05e2\u05dd \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9|last=|first=|date=|work=Maariv|access-date=|language=Hebrew}}</ref> Several investigations cleared Ronen of this accusation, but the [[Military Advocate General]]  recommended to the chief of staff to reconsider Ronen\u2019s promotion. This, as well as a personal feud between Ronen and IAF commander General [[David Ivry]], resulted in Ronen being denied promotion.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn November 1981 Ronen retired from the IDF with the rank of brigadier general having flown over 350 combat sorties.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/135628|title=Moskowitz Prize for Zionism 2010|last=|first=|date=|work=Arutz Sheva|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Air to air victories==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Number'''\n|'''Date'''\n|'''Ronen's plane'''\n|'''Enemy plane'''\n|'''Weapon used''' \n|'''Details'''\n|-\n|1\n|13 November 1966\n|Mirage III\n|Jordanian Hawker Hunter\n|Cannon\n|In the IAF's longest dogfight ever, against [[Muwaffaq Salti]], the commander of the Jordanian Hunter Squadron\n|-\n|2\n|7 April 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Syrian MiG-21\n|Cannon\n|During a mass air battle over the [[Golan Heights]]\n|-\n|3\n|5 June 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-19\n|Cannon\n|Over Ghardaka, Part of Operation Moked\n|-\n|4\n|5 June 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-19\n|Cannon\n|Second kill of the same battle\n|-\n|5\n|5 June 1967\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-21\n|[[Shafrir-2]]\n|During a mass air battle over the [[Nile Delta]]\n|-\n|6\n|21 May 1969\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-21\n|Cannon\n|Over [[Ismailia|Ismailla]]\n|-\n|7\n|11 September 1969\n|Mirage III\n|Egyptian MiG-21\n|[[AIM-9 Sidewinder|Sidewinder]]\n|During a mass air battle over the [[Nile Delta]]\n|}\n\n==After his retirement from the IDF==\nRonen worked as deputy director of the advertising agency Dahaf.\n\nIn 1989 he was appointed Consul General of Israel in Los Angeles and Hebraized his surname to Ronen. He served for three years.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 1992 he founded the Zahala Project, which works with at-risk teenagers to instill the values of Zionism and social responsibility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aluma.org.il/program/yedidut-zahala/|title=Yedidut Zahala {{!}} \u05d0\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05d4|website=aluma.org.il|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref> The project was adopted by the Ministry of Education, and defined by Education Minister [[Zevulun Hammer]] as a \"national project\". For his work with Zahala, Ronen (along with Ruth Dayan) was awarded the Yigal Alon Prize. His mentor and former commander Ezer Weizman was honored with giving him the award.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2002 he published his autobiography ''Eagle in the Sky'' in Hebrew. An English version was released in 2016 with a foreword by [[Dan Halutz]], a former commander of the IAF.\n\nIn 2007 he was featured in two episodes of the History Channel's ''[[Dogfights (TV series)|Dogfights]]''. In \"Dogfights of the Middle East\" Ronen covers the battle of Ghardaka and the defection of an Iraqi MiG-21, and in \"Desert Aces\" he relates his downing of the Jordanian Hawker Hunter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearethemighty.com/articles/israel-recently-buried-ran-ronen-an-ace-few-ever-heard-of|title=Israel recently buried Ran Ronen, an ace few ever heard of|date=2017-01-16|website=We Are The Mighty|language=en|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he won the [[Moskowitz Prize for Zionism]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moskowitzprize.com/en/award-winners/2008-winners/ran-pecker-ronen|title=Award winners 2008 Ran Pecker Ronen}}</ref> The award committee explained the decision to honor Ronen \"The prize is awarded for being an exemplary example of courage, sacrifice and leadership, for his exceptional handling of the educational and ethical challenges facing Zionism, and for his success in establishing the Zahala project, by recruiting former officers and commanders to the forefront of social action for Israeli youth.\"\n\nRonen was the sole owner of Pekker Enterprises, an advisory firm.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nFrom 2009 to 2012 he was a member of the Board of Directors of [[Israel Aerospace Industries]].\n\nIn 2013 his book ''Diary of Operations'' was published by ''[[Yedioth Ahronoth]]''. It is based on his previous book, but focuses on the operational issues.\n\n==Academic achievements==\nHe held a Master's degree in Public Administration from Harvard University and served as a Research Fellow at the [[Brookings Institution]] and at the [[RAND Corporation]].\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Ran Pecker memorial in Herzliya.jpg|thumb|Memorial to Ran Ronen at a [[roundabout]] in [[Herzliya]]]]\nAt the age of 21, Ronen married Herutah,<ref name=\":7\" /> whom he met at the age of eight, and the couple had three children.  After thirty years of marriage, the couple divorced.  His second wife was singer Mali Bronstein , whom he later divorced.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nRan Ronen died of blood cancer on December 3, 2016.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Muwaffaq Salti Air Base]]\n* [[List of Israeli flying aces]]\n* [[Giora Romm]]\n* [[Giora Epstein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mRoK3hLHvrk Moskowitz Prize 2008 on youtube]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0950883/?ref_=ttep_ep11 ''Dogfights of the Middle east'' on IMDb]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1084220/?ref_=ttep_ep5 ''Deserts Aces'' on IMDb]\n* [http://www.iaf.org.il/4451-47021-en/IAF.aspx Ran Ronen on the IAF website]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/keyword/ran-ronen Articles in the LA times about Ran Ronen]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ronen-Pekker, Ran}}\n[[Category:Israeli flying aces]]\n[[Category:Israeli Air Force generals]]\n[[Category:Israeli diplomats]]\n[[Category:RAND Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Brookings Institution]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moskowitz Prize for Zionism laureates]]\n", "name_user": "Hydromania", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ran_Ronen-Pekker"}
{"title_page": "Really Don't Care", "text_new": "{{Short description|2014 single by Demi Lovato}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Really Don't Care\n| cover      = Demi Lovato Really Don't Care (Official Single Cover).png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Demi Lovato]] featuring [[Cher Lloyd]]\n| album      = [[Demi (album)|Demi]]\n| B-side     = [[Nightingale (Demi Lovato song)|Nightingale]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|5|20}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=21}}\n| label      = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Demi Lovato]]|[[Carl Falk]]|[[Savan Kotecha]]|[[Rami Yacoub]]|[[Cher Lloyd]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Carl Falk|Rami Yacoub}}\n| chronology = [[Demi Lovato]]\n| prev_title = [[Somebody to You]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Up (Olly Murs song)|Up]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Cher Lloyd]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Sirens (Cher Lloyd song)|Sirens]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = Really Don't Care\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[Activated]]\n | next_year  = 2016\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Really Don't Care'''\" is a song by American singer [[Demi Lovato]], featuring English singer [[Cher Lloyd]]. The song was released on May 20, 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |title=Top 40/Mainstream > Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PhFKbyFS |archivedate=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=June 27, 2014}}</ref> as the fourth and final single from her fourth studio album ''[[Demi (album)|Demi]]'' (2013). The two co-wrote the song along with [[Savan Kotecha]] and its producers [[Carl Falk]] and [[Rami Yacoub]]. The song has been certified platinum by [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. \"Really Don't Care\" is Lovato's third number one on the US Dance chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2014-09-06/dance-club-play-songs|title=Hot Dance Club Songs |work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |date= September 6, 2014|accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Really Don't Care\" is an uptempo [[dance-pop]] song, with influences of [[bubblegum pop]],<ref name=\"billboard demi review\">{{cite web|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=Demi Lovato, 'Demi': Track-By-Track Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1561233/demi-lovato-demi-track-by-track-review|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref> that runs for three minutes and twenty-one seconds. Lloyd makes a brief appearance during the bridge. Lyrically, the song is a message of defiance to a former lover, with Lovato confidently singing such lines as, \"Even if the stars and moon collide, I never want you back into my life.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Erin|first=Adrienne|title=Pop Topper of the Week: Demi Lovato \u2013 'Really Don't Care' (feat. Cher Lloyd)|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/Adrienne_Erin/2013/05/14/pop_topper_of_the_week_demi_lovato_re|publisher=StarPulse.com|accessdate=October 13, 2013}}</ref> The song is set in the key of [[G major]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Demi Lovato \"Really Don't Care\" Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0117972&|publisher=Music Notes|accessdate=October 13, 2013}}</ref>\nLovato originally wrote the song as a breakup song. She wanted to make it a more empowering song. Lovato said in an interview, \"I wanted to make it more empowering. When I thought of the lyrics 'really don\u2019t care', it made me think of bullying, and made me think of the LGBT community, who deal with that so often, but they accept themselves.\"<ref name=LGBT>{{cite web|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2014/06/70450/demi-lovato-pride-parade|title=Demi Lovato Really, Truly Has Pride|author=Norris, John|date=2014-06-30|accessdate=2014-06-30}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' writer Jason Lipshutz praised Lovato's \"sassy\" confidence on the track, which effectively showcases her \"overpowering pipes\". He also commented positively on the placement of the song on the track list, noting that \"Really Don't Care\" serves a \"buoyant reprieve\" after more emotionally heavy tracks.<ref name=\"billboard demi review\"/> Sam Lansky of ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' described the song as \"irresistibly spunky\", but found Lloyd's short feature to be superfluous.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lansky|first=Sam|title=Demi Lovato\u2019s \u2018Demi\u2019: Album Review|url=http://www.idolator.com/7457954/demi-lovato-demi-album-review/|work=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|publisher=[[Spin Media]]|accessdate=October 13, 2013}}</ref> [[4Music]] called the song \"a brilliant break-up survival anthem that sticks it to every annoying ex ever\".<ref name=\"4music\">{{cite episode |title=This Week's Fresh Music Top 20|series=Fresh Music Top 20|network=[[4Music]]|airdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> On the other hand, Melinda Newman of ''[[HitFix]]'' found the song to be too generic, comparing it to [[Icona Pop]]'s breakout hit \"[[I Love It (Icona Pop song)|I Love It]]\" (2012).<ref>{{cite news|last=Newman|first=Melinda|title=Demi Lovato's new album 'Demi': Review|url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/demi-lovatos-new-album-demi-review|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=October 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nBefore it was released as a single, \"Really Don't Care\" debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 98. After it was released as a single, it peaked at number 26 making it Lovato's eighth top 40 entry on the Hot 100 and making Cher Lloyd's third entry on that chart and second top 40 single since her song \"[[Want U Back]]\". On the US Dance Chart, it became Lovato's third number one and Lloyd's first number one on that chart. As of October 2017, \"Really Don't Care\" has sold over 952,000 digital downloads in the United States.<ref name=\"ussales\">{{cite news|title=Ask Billboard: Demi Lovato's Career Album & Song Sales|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7998706/demi-lovato-21-savage-tom-petty-ask-billboard|work=Billboard|date=October 15, 2017|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Music videos ==\n=== Background and synopsis ===\nThe official music video was released on June 26, 2014, although few teasers for the video were previously uploaded on Lovato's official [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web |last=Malkin |first=Marc |title=Demi Lovato's New Teaser for Her 'Really Don't Care' Video\u2014See It Now! |url=http://uk.eonline.com/news/554165/demi-lovato-s-new-teaser-for-her-really-don-t-care-video-see-it-now |work=E! Online |accessdate=June 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"eonline-554728\">{{cite web |date=June 26, 2014 |last=Johnson |first=Zach |title=Demi Lovato's 'Really Don't Care' Music Video Features a Surprise Cameo From Wilmer Valderrama! |url=http://de.eonline.com/news/554728/demi-lovato-s-really-don-t-care-music-video-features-a-surprise-cameo-from-wilmer-valderrama |work=E! Online |accessdate=June 26, 2014}}</ref> The video starts off with Lovato expressing her support for the LGBT community and saying that ''\"[her] Jesus loves all.\"'' After that, the music starts and Lovato is seen singing her single at the parade. The video was filmed on June 8, 2014 at the [[Pride parade|LA Pride Parade]] and features cameo appearances from [[Perez Hilton]], [[Kat Graham]], [[Shane Bitney Crone]], [[BriaAndChrissy|Bria Kam and Chrissy Chambers]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/BriaAndChrissy/ Bria and Chrissy's YouTube channel] YouTube.com</ref> [[John Lloyd Taylor|John Taylor]], [[Travis Barker]] and [[Wilmer Valderrama]].<ref name=\"eonline-554728\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Ableson |first=Jon |title=Demi Lovato Releases 'Really Don't Care' (ft. Cher Lloyd) Music Video |url=http://www.alterthepress.com/2014/06/demi-lovato-releases-really-dont-care.html |work=Alter The Press! |accessdate=June 26, 2014}}</ref> Cher Lloyd also appears during the bridge part of the song. It was directed by [[Ryan Pallotta]], who collaborated with Lovato from her previous music videos, \"[[Neon Lights (Demi Lovato song)|Neon Lights]]\" and \"[[Made in the USA (Demi Lovato song)|Made in the USA]]\".\n\n=== Lyric video ===\nThe lyric video was uploaded on May 14, 2014 on Lovato's [[Vevo]] account. The video features the lyrics of the song above several shots of Brazilian fans [[lip sync]]ing the song as well as some scenes from concerts where Lovato performs the song during the [[Neon Lights Tour|concert tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ryanseacrest.com/2014/05/14/demi-lovato-fans-star-in-really-dont-care-lyric-video/|title=Demi Lovato Fans Star in \u2018Really Don\u2019t Care\u2019 Lyric Video|publisher=Ryan Seacrest|last=Perricone|first=Kathleen|accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> During the video, Lovato makes an appearance to surprise some of the fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1824601/watch-demi-lovato-prank-these-lovatics-in-her-really-dont-care-lyric-video/|title=Watch Demi Lovato Prank These Lovatics In Her \u2018Really Don\u2019t Care\u2019 Lyric Video|publisher=[[MTV]]|accessdate=May 14, 2014|last=Garibaldi|first=Christina}}</ref> At the end, a message is displayed to thank the Brazilian fans for helping out with the filming of the lyric video.\n\n==Live performances==\nLovato performed the song on several occasions before its official release as a single. Once released in May 2014, performances include on the Season 13 Live Final of American Idol,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanidol.com/videos/season_xiii_performances/idol-finale-demi-lovato-top-13-girls-really-dont-care-and-neon-lights|title=Idol Finale - Demi Lovato & Top 13 Girls \"Really Don't Care\" and \"Neon Lights\"|accessdate=February 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819091051/http://www.americanidol.com/videos/season_xiii_performances/idol-finale-demi-lovato-top-13-girls-really-dont-care-and-neon-lights |archivedate=August 19, 2014 }}</ref> ''[[Good Morning America]]'' Summer Concert Series, ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'', and the [[2014 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Torrelio|first1=Sebastian|title=Best and Worst of the 2014 Teen Choice Awards|url=https://variety.com/2014/scene/vpage/teen-choice-awards-best-and-worst-2014-1201280075/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=August 16, 2014|date=August 11, 2014}}</ref> The song was also included in the setlists for [[The Neon Lights Tour]] and the [[Demi World Tour]]. Furthermore, the song was part of Lovato's setlist at the 2015 [[iHeartRadio Music Festival]] on September 18\u201319, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=iHeartRadio Music Festival 2015 Day 1: 41 Things You Have to See|last=Atkinson|first=Katie|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/6700626/iheartradio-music-festival-what-you-missed|accessdate=October 18, 2015|date=September 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Award\n!scope=\"col\"|Category\n!scope=\"col\"|Work\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2014\n| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| \"Song of the Summer/DJ Replay\"\n|rowspan=\"7\"|\"Really Don't Care\"\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Awards]]\n|\"Best Lyric Video\"\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice Music \u2013 Summer Song|Choice Summer Song]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice Music - Break-Up Song|Choice Break-Up Song]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Radio Disney Music Awards]]\n| Best Breakup Song\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best Collaboration\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n==Formats and track listings==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n*'''Digital download (Remixes EP)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/really-dont-care-remixes-ep/id908195817|title=Really Don't Care Remixes - EP by Demi Lovato on Apple Music|website=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (feat. Cher Lloyd) - 3:20\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (DJLW Remix) - 4:30\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (Toy Armada & DJ GRIND Remix)- 5:35\n#\"Really Don't Care\" ([[Cole Plante]] Remix) - 5:07\n#\"Really Don't Care\" ([[Digital Dog]] Club Remix) - 5:07\n\n*'''Digital download (Remixes)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/really-dont-care-remixes-single/id894755822|title=Really Don't Care Remixes - Single by Demi Lovato on Apple Music|website=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (Cole Plante Remix) - 5:07\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (Cole Plante Radio Remix) - 3:37\n\n*'''Digital download (EP)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/really-dont-care-ep/id910462828|title=Really Don't Care - EP by Demi Lovato on Apple Music|website=itunes.apple.com|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (feat. Cher Lloyd) - 3:21\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (DJLW Radio Edit) - 3:14\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (Cole Plante Radio Remix) - 3:37\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (Digital Dog Radio Remix) - 3:19\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (Toy Armada & DJ GRIND Radio Remix)- 3:40\n#\"Demi in London\" (Video) - 2:22\n*'''Digital and download'''\n#\"Really Don't Care\" (feat. [[Cher Lloyd]]) - 3:21\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2013\u201314)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web |last=Gavin |first=Gavin |date=May 19, 2013 |