{"title_page": "Cow and Chicken", "text_new": "{{short description|American animated comedy television series created by David Feiss}}\n{{Infobox television\n| image = Cow and Chicken logo.png\n| genre = {{unbulleted list|[[Comedy]]|[[Surreal humour]]|[[Slapstick]]|[[Slice of life]]}}\n| creator = [[David Feiss]]\n| writer = {{unbulleted list|Pilar Menendez|[[David Feiss]]|Monte Young|Victor Ortado|[[Larry Huber]]|Vincent Davis|Greg Emison||Gordon Coulthart|Michael Ryan|[[Bill Burnett (writer)|Bill Burnett]]|[[Steve Marmel]]|[[Vincent Waller]]|[[Seth MacFarlane]]|[[Richard Pursel]]|[[Maxwell Atoms]]|Sherri Schrader|Jeff Kwitny|Gary Wilson|Sami Rank|[[Genndy Tartakovsky]]|[[Scott Morse]]|Nora Johnson|Fred Belford}}\n| director = {{unbulleted list|David Feiss|'''Co-directors:'''|[[John McIntyre (cartoonist)|John McIntyre]] <small>(1 episode)</small>|Monte Young <small>(1 episode)</small>|[[Robert Alvarez]] <small>(15 episodes)</small>}}\n| voices = {{unbulleted list|[[Charlie Adler]]|[[Dee Bradley Baker]]|[[Candi Milo]]|[[Howard Morris]]|[[Dan Castellaneta]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Guy Moon]]\n| opentheme = \"Cow and Chicken\"\n| endtheme = \"Cow and Chicken\" <small>(Instrumental)</small>\n| composer = Guy Moon\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 3\n| num_episodes = 52 (104 segments)\n| list_episodes = List of Cow and Chicken episodes\n| executive_producer = [[Brian A. Miller]]<br />[[Sherry Gunther]] <small>(seasons 1\u20132)</small><br />[[Larry Huber]] <small>(season 1)</small><br />[[Buzz Potamkin]] <small>(Pilot only)</small><br />'''For Cartoon Network <small>(seasons 3\u20134)</small>:''' Linda Simensky <small>(seasons 3\u20134)</small> and Khaki Jones <small>(seasons 3\u20134)</small>\n| producer = {{unbulleted list|[[David Feiss]]|Vincent Davis|[[Davis Doi]] <small>(supervising producer, seasons 2\u20133)</small>}}\n| runtime = 14 minutes\n| company = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Cartoons]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_run = United States\n| first_aired = {{Start date|1997|7|15}}\n| last_aired  = {{End date|1999|7|24}}\n| related = ''[[I Am Weasel]]''<br />''[[What a Cartoon!]]''\n| website = https://web.archive.org/web/19991013050338/http://cartoonnetwork.com/doc/cowchicken/main.html\n| production_website = https://web.archive.org/web/20050829134816/http://david-feiss.netfirms.com/\n| channel = [[Cartoon Network]]\n}}\n\n'''''Cow and Chicken''''' is an American [[cartoon series|animated]] [[television comedy|comedy]] television series created by [[David Feiss]] for [[Cartoon Network]], and the 3rd of the network's [[Cartoon Cartoons]]. It follows the [[surreal humor|surreal]] adventures of two [[funny animal]] siblings, Cow and Chicken. They are often antagonized by the Red Guy, a cartoon [[Satan|Devil]] who poses as various characters to scam them.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=138-139 }}</ref>\n\nThe original pilot appeared as an episode of the animation showcase series ''[[What a Cartoon!]]''. The popularity of the original short allowed [[Hanna-Barbera]] to give it the green light for a full series, which premiered on July 15, 1997. Originally, ''Cow and Chicken'' was attached to another segment called ''[[I Am Weasel]]'', which was later spun-off into [[I Am Weasel|its own half-hour series]] on June 10, 1999. The series was produced by Hanna-Barbera Cartoons. It was nominated for two [[Emmy Award]]s.\n\n==Premise==\n[[File:Cow and Chicken No Smoking Poster.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Poster for the series' pilot, featuring the Red Guy (''left''), Cow (''center''), and Chicken (''right'').]]\nThe series focuses on the misadventures of two unlikely yet somehow biological siblings: the sweet-natured, dim, ecstatic, [[anthropomorphic]] Cow Steer and her cynical older brother Chicken Steer (both voiced by [[Charlie Adler]]). The two are often caught in escapades with their flamboyant enemy, the Red Guy (Adler), who disguises himself under various personas to attempt to scam them.\n\nSupporting characters include Chicken and Cow's [[wikt:delirious|delirious]] human parents Dad and Mom ([[Dee Bradley Baker]] and [[Candi Milo]], respectively), only seen from the waist down; Chicken's best friends Flem ([[Howard Morris]]) and Earl ([[Dan Castellaneta]]); and his [[cousin]], Boneless Chicken (Adler).\n\nThe series draws on eccentric, surreal, grotesque, and repulsive humor. For example, Cow and Chicken always order \"pork butts and taters\" in the cafeteria, the Red Guy always shows his butt, and characters often pepper their speech with malapropisms and sarcasm. The humor and storylines depicted are often based on traditional childhood worries, anxieties, or phobias such as [[cooties]] or venturing into the girls' restroom, but enhanced comically.\n\nMany of the slapstick antics involve Cow getting physically abused. Because [[Hinduism]] considers the cow a sacred animal, the series was largely ignored in India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tickling the Global Funny Bone: Cartoon Network Tweaks Shows to Click with Humor Around the World|first=Matt|last=Kempner|date=March 6, 2002|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|department=Atlanta & the World|page=4E}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nDavid Feiss first created ''Cow and Chicken'' as a story for his daughter.<ref name=\"creation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetworkla.com/english/watch/creator/dfeiss.html|title=Animator Profile: David Feiss|work=cartoonnetworkla.com|publisher=Cartoon Network|access-date=2007-07-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516002446/http://www.cartoonnetworkla.com/english/watch/creator/dfeiss.html|archivedate=2006-05-16}}</ref> Feiss was an animator who had worked with [[Hanna-Barbera]] and related projects since 1978.<ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nYears later, Feiss was called to submit ideas for ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'', a series of various animated shorts from numerous creators and writers. Feiss submitted three ideas to executive producer [[Larry Huber]], one of which was ''Cow and Chicken''.<ref name=\"wac\">{{cite web|url=http://www.h2g2.com/approved_entry/A767289|title=Cow and Chicken, and I Am Weasel&nbsp;\u2014 two animated cartoon series|work=h2g2|publisher=BBC|date=2002-09-05|access-date=2007-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801091909/http://www.h2g2.com/approved_entry/A767289|archive-date=2013-08-01|url-status=live}}</ref> Cow and Chicken premiered on ''What a Cartoon!'' in 1995. Later, Hanna-Barbera decided to turn ''Cow and Chicken'' into a full series, following many letters from fans asking for more.<ref name=\"wac\"/>\n\n===Voice actors===\nA single actor, [[Charlie Adler]], voiced the three leading roles of Cow, Chicken, and the Red Guy. Supporting voices included [[Candi Milo]] and [[Dee Bradley Baker]] as Mom and Dad, and [[Dan Castellaneta]] and [[Howard Morris]] as Earl and Flem.\n\nGuest stars included Feiss, [[Will Ferrell]], [[Carlos Alazraqui]], [[Tom Kenny]], [[Jill Talley]], [[Dom DeLuise]], [[Michael Gough (voice actor)|Michael Gough]], [[Mark Hamill]], [[Jess Harnell]], [[Pamela Adlon]], and many others.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Cow and Chicken episodes}}\n{{:List of Cow and Chicken episodes}}\n''Cow and Chicken'' has a total of 52 episodes in 3 seasons that were produced from November 1996 to April 1999. Each half-hour contains 2 ''Cow and Chicken'' and 1 ''I Am Weasel'' segment.<ref name=\"feiss\">{{cite web|title=Episode Guide: Cow and Chicken and I Am Weasel|author=Feiss, David|url=http://david-feiss.netfirms.com/episodes.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212174713/http://david-feiss.netfirms.com/episodes.html|archivedate=2006-12-12|date=January 12, 2000|access-date=2011-07-05}}</ref> ''Cow and Chicken'' premiered as a full half-hour on July 15, 1997.<ref name=\"gallo\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1997/tv/reviews/cow-and-chicken-1117341278/|title=Cow and Chicken|first=Phil|last=Gallo|date=July 15, 1997|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|access-date=2013-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003015429/http://variety.com/1997/tv/reviews/cow-and-chicken-1117341278/|archive-date=October 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The series ran for 52 episodes through 1999. As a supporting segment, the show included a cartoon called ''I Am Weasel''; this segment was spun off as an independent series late in the show's run. Typically, an episode would consist of two seven-minute ''Cow and Chicken'' shorts playing back-to-back, then followed by a seven-minute ''I Am Weasel'' short before the end credits.<ref name=\"gallo\"/> The exception to this structure was episode 105 (\"The Ugliest Weenie\"), which had the ''Weasel'' short (\"I Are Big Star\") play in-between the two ''Cow and Chicken'' shorts, possibly because said shorts were one storyline.\n\nReruns continued to be shown on Cartoon Network from 1999 to 2003, and again from 2005 to 2008 as part of the network's blocks titled ''[[The Cartoon Cartoon Show]]'' and ''Top 5''.\n\n===Controversial episode===\nThe second season segment \"Buffalo Gals\", first paired with \"Cow and Chicken Reclining\", was banned by Cartoon Network after receiving one letter of complaint from a parent about the episode's liberal visual and verbal innuendo about the titular biker group being lesbians. In the segment, the Buffalo Gals break into people's homes to chew on the carpet, a biker named Munch Kelly has a carpet swatch for a calling card, and when Dad freaks out over the Buffalo Gals in the house, Mom says, \"They're not after you.\"<ref name=\"buffalo1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_18672_the-6-creepiest-things-ever-slipped-into-childrens-cartoons.html|title=The 6 Creepiest Things Ever Slipped Into Children's Cartoons|author=Anthony Scibelli|date=August 6, 2010|publisher=[[Cracked (magazine)|Cracked]]|access-date=January 16, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511114141/http://www.cracked.com/article_18672_the-6-creepiest-things-ever-slipped-into-childrens-cartoons.html|archive-date=May 11, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the Buffalo Gals play softball and talk about pitching and catching. Although it was only shown on air once, it was replaced by \"Orthodontic Police\" in future airings, including on [[Netflix]] streaming and reruns on [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]]. The episode was also discussed on an installment of [[Rob Paulsen]]'s ''Talkin' Toons'' special featuring ''Cow and Chicken'' creator David Feiss and voice actor [[Charlie Adler]] when an audience member asked why \"Buffalo Gals\" only aired once.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee(s) !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1996 || [[Annie Award]] || [[Annie Award for Best Animated Short Subject|Best Animated Short Subject]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=24th Annie Award Winners Announced|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.9/articles/news1.9.html|date=December 1996|issue=9|journal=Animation World Magazine|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|volume=1|access-date=2013-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131083922/http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.9/articles/news1.9.html|archive-date=2013-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Hanna-Barbera]]<br />{{small|for \"No Smoking\"}} || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]] || [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming One Hour or Less)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/cow-and-chicken-no-smoking|title=Cow And Chicken in No Smoking|work=[[Emmys.com]]|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=2013-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728013813/http://www.emmys.com/shows/cow-and-chicken-no-smoking|archive-date=2014-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Buzz Potamkin]], [[Larry Huber]], [[David Feiss]], Pilar Menendez, and Sam Kieth<br />{{small|for \"No Smoking\"}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997 || rowspan=\"4\"|[[Annie Award]] || Best Individual Achievement: Storyboarding in a TV Production<ref>{{cite web|title=25th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (1997)|url=http://annieawards.org/25th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=[[ASIFA-Hollywood]]|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230210843/http://annieawards.org/25th-annie-awards|archive-date=2015-12-30|url-status=live}}</ref> || Nora Johnson<br />{{small|for \"Orthodontic Police\"}} || {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"|1998 || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Music in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a98\">{{cite web|title=26th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (1998)|url=http://annieawards.org/26th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130223120846/http://annieawards.org/26th-annie-awards|archive-date=2013-02-23|url-status=live}}</ref> || Bill Burnett and [[Guy Moon]]<br />{{small|for \"The Ugliest Weenie, Part 2\"}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Producing in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a98\"/> || Vincent Davis || {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Individual Achievement for Storyboarding in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a98\"/> || [[Maxwell Atoms]]<br />{{small|for \"The Karate Chick\"}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Award]] || Best Sound Editing&nbsp;\u2014 Sound Effects<ref name=\"gr98\">{{cite web|title=Motion Picture Sound Editors, USA (1998)|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000452/1998|work=[[IMDb]]|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410152116/http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000452/1998|archive-date=2015-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref> || Greg LaPlante || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Sound Editing&nbsp;\u2014 Television Animated Series<ref name=\"gr98\"/> || [[Cartoon Network]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Sound Editing&nbsp;\u2014 Television Animation&nbsp;\u2014 Music<ref name=\"gr98\"/> || Cartoon Network || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]] || [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming One Hour or Less)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/cow-and-chicken|title=Cow And Chicken|work=Emmys.com|publisher=Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|access-date=2013-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151147/http://www.emmys.com/shows/cow-and-chicken|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Davis Doi]], Vincent Davis, David Feiss, [[Steve Marmel]], [[Richard Pursel]], and Michael Ryan<br />{{small|for \"Free Inside!/Journey to the Center of Cow\"}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1999 || [[Annie Award]] || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Voice Acting in an Animated Television Production<ref>{{cite web|title=27th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (1999)|url=http://annieawards.org/27th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401040333/http://annieawards.org/27th-annie-awards|archive-date=2014-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Charlie Adler]]<br />{{small|as Cow}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Award]] || Best Sound Editing&nbsp;\u2014 Television Animated Series&nbsp;\u2014 Sound<ref name=\"gr99\">{{cite web|title=Motion Picture Sound Editors, USA (1999)|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000452/1999|work=IMDb|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601004002/http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000452/1999|archive-date=2013-06-01|url-status=live}}</ref> || Cartoon Network || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Sound Editing&nbsp;\u2014 Television Animation&nbsp;\u2014 Music<ref name=\"gr99\"/> || Cartoon Network || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2000 ||  Best Sound Editing&nbsp;\u2014 Television Animation&nbsp;\u2014 Music<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion Picture Sound Editors, USA (2000)|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000452/2000|work=IMDb|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823115528/http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000452/2000|archive-date=2011-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> || Roy Braverman<br />{{small|for \"A Couple of Skating Fools\"}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2000 || [[Annie Award]] || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Voice Acting in an Animated Television Production || [[Charlie Adler]]<br />{{small|as Cow}} || {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Other media==\nThe two main characters, Cow and Chicken, made cameo appearances as aliens in ''[[Ben 10: Omniverse]]''. They were the second Cartoon Network characters to make cameo appearances in the ''Ben 10'' franchise, Billy from ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]'' being the first. Adler reprised his roles for the cameo.\n\nChicken made a cameo near the end of the ''[[Cartoon Planet]]'' episode \" Tom Foolery\".\n\nCow makes a cameo in the beginning of ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]'' episode \"Herbicidal Maniac\" giving General Skarr fertilizer.\n\nDuring the ''[[Mad (TV series)|Mad]]'' episode \"Once Upon a Toon\", Cow and Chicken are among the classic cartoon characters reunited in a spoof of ABC's ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''.\n\nIn the ''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]'' episode \"''[[Crossover Nexus]]''\", Chicken and I.M. Weasel (with [[Michael Dorn]] reprising his role as Weasel for a speaking cameo) made  cameo appearances as two of the Cartoon Network heroes that were summoned by Strike, and also Cow (as SuperCow) appears as one the Cartoon Network heroes that [[Ben Tennyson]] (''[[Ben 10 (2016 TV series)|Ben 10]]'') shapeshifts into.\n\n===Home media===\n''Cow and Chicken: Season 1'', a two-disc set featuring the complete first season which contains 13 complete episodes, was released by [[Madman Entertainment]] in [[Australia]] ([[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] [[PAL]]) on September 12, 2007.<ref name=\"Madman1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.madman.com.au/catalogue/view/8799/cow-and-chicken-season-1|title=Cow and Chicken Season 1|work=Madman.com.au|publisher=Madman Entertainment|access-date=2012-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411070308/http://www.madman.com.au/catalogue/view/8799/cow-and-chicken-season-1|archive-date=2012-04-11|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Season 2'' came out on February 10, 2010, by the same company in Australia.<ref name=\"Madman2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.madman.com.au/catalogue/view/12205/cow-and-chicken-season-2|title=Cow and Chicken Season 2|work=Madman.com.au|publisher=Madman Entertainment|access-date=2012-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430192532/http://www.madman.com.au/catalogue/view/12205/cow-and-chicken-season-2|archive-date=2012-04-30|url-status=live}}</ref> The entire series got partially released on DVD in Thailand as 4 season sets, containing Thai and English audio, with the segment \"Buffalo Gals\" banned from these releases.\n\nThe video game ''[[Cartoon Network Racing]]'' contains the episodes \"Black Sheep of the Family\" and \"Child Star\" (PS2 version only) as unlockable extras.\n\nAll 4 seasons were released on iTunes and Amazon as of August 16, 2018.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Title !! Format !! DVD Region !! Country !! Distributor !! Release date !! Ref.\n|-\n| ''Cartoon Cartoons: Cow and Chicken''\n| VHS\n| {{N/A}}\n| United States\n| Cartoon Network\n| 1998\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Cartoon Cartoons: Cow and Chicken {{!}} VHSCollector.com |url=https://vhscollector.com/movie/cartoon-cartoons-cow-and-chicken |website=vhscollector.com |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Cow and Chicken: Season 1''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | DVD\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 4\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Australia\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Madman Entertainment\n| September 12, 2007\n| <ref name=\"Madman1\"/>\n|-\n| ''Cow and Chicken: Season 2''\n| February 10, 2010\n| <ref name=\"Madman2\"/>\n|}\n\n'''American releases'''\n* Cartoon Network Halloween: \"Cow with Four Eyes\"\n* Cartoon Network Christmas: \"Me an' My Dog\"\n\n===Video games===\nCow, Chicken, and the Red Guy are playable characters in the game ''Cartoon Network Racing''. The PlayStation 2 version includes Flem and Earl as playable characters.\n\nCow/Supercow, Chicken, and the Red Guy are playable characters in the game ''[[Cartoon Network Speedway]]''.\n\nIn the video game ''[[FusionFall]]'', one of the character items is based on ''Cow and Chicken''. Cow and Chicken's cousin, Boneless Chicken, can also be seen on a billboard in the game. Though not in the game, Cow is seen as Supercow as a statue at Mt. Neverest.\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|1=Cartoon Network|3=Cartoon Cartoons}}\n* ''[[I Am Weasel]]\n* ''[[Cartoon Cartoons]]\n* ''[[The Ren & Stimpy Show]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Cow and Chicken}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/19991013050338/http://cartoonnetwork.com/doc/cowchicken/main.html ''Cow and Chicken''] at [[Cartoon Network]]'s Department of Cartoons (archive)\n* {{IMDb title|0118289}}\n* {{tv.com show|cow-and-chicken}}\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/A-C/Cow_and_Chicken/Cow_and_Chicken/index.html ''Cow and Chicken''] at the [[Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n\n{{Annie Award for Best Animated Short Subject}}\n{{Cartoon Network original programming}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cartoon Network|Cartoon|1990s|Television|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cow And Chicken}}\n[[Category:1997 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1999 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about siblings]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Short Subject Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network original programming]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Cartoons]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in television]]\n[[Category:The Devil in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about cows]]\n[[Category:Television series about chickens]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:Television series created by David Feiss]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American animated comedy television series created by David Feiss}}\n{{Infobox television\n| image = Cow and Chicken logo.png\n| genre = {{unbulleted list|[[Comedy]]|[[Surreal humour]]|[[Slapstick]]|[[Slice of life]]}}\n| creator = [[David Feiss]]\n| writer = {{unbulleted list|Pilar Menendez|[[David Feiss]]|Monte Young|Victor Ortado|[[Larry Huber]]|Vincent Davis|Greg Emison||Gordon Coulthart|Michael Ryan|[[Bill Burnett (writer)|Bill Burnett]]|[[Steve Marmel]]|[[Vincent Waller]]|[[Seth MacFarlane]]|[[Richard Pursel]]|[[Maxwell Atoms]]|Sherri Schrader|Jeff Kwitny|Gary Wilson|Sami Rank|[[Genndy Tartakovsky]]|[[Scott Morse]]|Nora Johnson|Fred Belford}}\n| director = {{unbulleted list|David Feiss|'''Co-directors:'''|[[John McIntyre (cartoonist)|John McIntyre]] <small>(1 episode)</small>|Monte Young <small>(1 episode)</small>|[[Robert Alvarez]] <small>(15 episodes)</small>}}\n| voices = {{unbulleted list|[[Charlie Adler]]|[[Dee Bradley Baker]]|[[Candi Milo]]|[[Howard Morris]]|[[Dan Castellaneta]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Guy Moon]]\n| opentheme = \"Cow and Chicken\"\n| endtheme = \"Cow and Chicken\" <small>(Instrumental)</small>\n| composer = Guy Moon\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 3\n| num_episodes = 52 (104 segments)\n| list_episodes = List of Cow and Chicken episodes\n| executive_producer = [[Brian A. Miller]]<br />[[Sherry Gunther]] <small>(seasons 1\u20132)</small><br />[[Larry Huber]] <small>(season 1)</small><br />[[Buzz Potamkin]] <small>(Pilot only)</small><br />'''For Cartoon Network <small>(seasons 3\u20134)</small>:''' Linda Simensky <small>(seasons 3\u20134)</small> and Khaki Jones <small>(seasons 3\u20134)</small>\n| producer = {{unbulleted list|[[David Feiss]]|Vincent Davis|[[Davis Doi]] <small>(supervising producer, seasons 2\u20133)</small>}}\n| runtime = 14 minutes\n| company = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Cartoons]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[SDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Surround]]\n| first_run = United States\n| first_aired = {{Start date|1997|7|15}}\n| last_aired  = {{End date|1999|7|24}}\n| related = ''[[I Am Weasel]]''<br />''[[What a Cartoon!]]''\n| website = https://web.archive.org/web/19991013050338/http://cartoonnetwork.com/doc/cowchicken/main.html\n| production_website = https://web.archive.org/web/20050829134816/http://david-feiss.netfirms.com/\n| channel = [[Cartoon Network]]\n}}\n\n'''''Cow and Chicken''''' is an American [[cartoon series|animated]] [[television comedy|comedy]] television series created by [[David Feiss]] for [[Cartoon Network]], and the 3rd of the network's [[Cartoon Cartoons]]. It follows the [[surreal humor|surreal]] adventures of two [[funny animal]] siblings, Cow and Chicken. They are often antagonized by the Red Guy, a cartoon [[Satan|Devil]] who poses as various characters to scam them.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=138-139 }}</ref>\n\nThe original pilot appeared as an episode of the animation showcase series ''[[What a Cartoon!]]''. The popularity of the original short allowed [[Hanna-Barbera]] to give it the green light for a full series, which premiered on July 15, 1997. Originally, ''Cow and Chicken'' was attached to another segment called ''[[I Am Weasel]]'', which was later spun-off into [[I Am Weasel|its own half-hour series]] on June 10, 1999. The series was produced by Hanna-Barbera Cartoons. It was nominated for two [[Emmy Award]]s.\n\n==Premise==\n[[File:Cow and Chicken No Smoking Poster.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Poster for the series' pilot, featuring the Red Guy (''left''), Cow (''center''), and Chicken (''right'').]]\nThe series focuses on the misadventures of two unlikely yet somehow biological siblings: the sweet-natured, dim, ecstatic, [[anthropomorphic]] Cow Steer and her cynical older brother Chicken Steer (both voiced by [[Charlie Adler]]). The two are often caught in escapades with their flamboyant enemy, the Red Guy (Adler), who disguises himself under various personas to attempt to scam them.\n\nSupporting characters include Chicken and Cow's [[wikt:delirious|delirious]] human parents Dad and Mom ([[Dee Bradley Baker]] and [[Candi Milo]]), only seen from the waist down; Chicken's best friends Flem ([[Howard Morris]]) and Earl ([[Dan Castellaneta]]); and his [[cousin]], Boneless Chicken (Adler).\n\nThe series draws on eccentric, surreal, grotesque, and repulsive humor. For example, Cow and Chicken always order \"pork butts and taters\" in the cafeteria, the Red Guy always shows his butt, and characters often pepper their speech with malapropisms and sarcasm. The humor and storylines depicted are often based on traditional childhood worries, anxieties, or phobias such as [[cooties]] or venturing into the girls' restroom, but enhanced comically.\n\nMany of the slapstick antics involve Cow getting physically abused. Because [[Hinduism]] considers the cow a sacred animal, the series was largely ignored in India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tickling the Global Funny Bone: Cartoon Network Tweaks Shows to Click with Humor Around the World|first=Matt|last=Kempner|date=March 6, 2002|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|department=Atlanta & the World|page=4E}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nDavid Feiss first created ''Cow and Chicken'' as a story for his daughter.<ref name=\"creation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetworkla.com/english/watch/creator/dfeiss.html|title=Animator Profile: David Feiss|work=cartoonnetworkla.com|publisher=Cartoon Network|access-date=2007-07-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516002446/http://www.cartoonnetworkla.com/english/watch/creator/dfeiss.html|archivedate=2006-05-16}}</ref> Feiss was an animator who had worked with [[Hanna-Barbera]] and related projects since 1978.<ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nYears later, Feiss was called to submit ideas for ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'', a series of various animated shorts from numerous creators and writers. Feiss submitted three ideas to executive producer [[Larry Huber]], one of which was ''Cow and Chicken''.<ref name=\"wac\">{{cite web|url=http://www.h2g2.com/approved_entry/A767289|title=Cow and Chicken, and I Am Weasel&nbsp;\u2014 two animated cartoon series|work=h2g2|publisher=BBC|date=2002-09-05|access-date=2007-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801091909/http://www.h2g2.com/approved_entry/A767289|archive-date=2013-08-01|url-status=live}}</ref> Cow and Chicken premiered on ''What a Cartoon!'' in 1995. Later, Hanna-Barbera decided to turn ''Cow and Chicken'' into a full series, following many letters from fans asking for more.<ref name=\"wac\"/>\n\n===Voice actors===\nA single actor, [[Charlie Adler]], voiced the three leading roles of Cow, Chicken, and the Red Guy. Supporting voices included [[Candi Milo]] and [[Dee Bradley Baker]] as Mom and Dad, and [[Dan Castellaneta]] and [[Howard Morris]] as Earl and Flem.\n\nGuest stars included Feiss, [[Will Ferrell]], [[Carlos Alazraqui]], [[Tom Kenny]], [[Jill Talley]], [[Dom DeLuise]], [[Michael Gough (voice actor)|Michael Gough]], [[Mark Hamill]], [[Jess Harnell]], [[Pamela Adlon]], and many others.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Cow and Chicken episodes}}\n{{:List of Cow and Chicken episodes}}\n''Cow and Chicken'' has a total of 52 episodes in 3 seasons that were produced from November 1996 to April 1999. Each half-hour contains 2 ''Cow and Chicken'' and 1 ''I Am Weasel'' segment.<ref name=\"feiss\">{{cite web|title=Episode Guide: Cow and Chicken and I Am Weasel|author=Feiss, David|url=http://david-feiss.netfirms.com/episodes.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212174713/http://david-feiss.netfirms.com/episodes.html|archivedate=2006-12-12|date=January 12, 2000|access-date=2011-07-05}}</ref> ''Cow and Chicken'' premiered as a full half-hour on July 15, 1997.<ref name=\"gallo\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1997/tv/reviews/cow-and-chicken-1117341278/|title=Cow and Chicken|first=Phil|last=Gallo|date=July 15, 1997|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|access-date=2013-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003015429/http://variety.com/1997/tv/reviews/cow-and-chicken-1117341278/|archive-date=October 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The series ran for 52 episodes through 1999. As a supporting segment, the show included a cartoon called ''I Am Weasel''; this segment was spun off as an independent series late in the show's run. Typically, an episode would consist of two seven-minute ''Cow and Chicken'' shorts playing back-to-back, then followed by a seven-minute ''I Am Weasel'' short before the end credits.<ref name=\"gallo\"/> The exception to this structure was episode 105 (\"The Ugliest Weenie\"), which had the ''Weasel'' short (\"I Are Big Star\") play in-between the two ''Cow and Chicken'' shorts, possibly because said shorts were one storyline.\n\nReruns continued to be shown on Cartoon Network from 1999 to 2003, and again from 2005 to 2008 as part of the network's blocks titled ''[[The Cartoon Cartoon Show]]'' and ''Top 5''.\n\n===Controversial episode===\nThe second season segment \"Buffalo Gals\", first paired with \"Cow and Chicken Reclining\", was banned by Cartoon Network after receiving one letter of complaint from a parent about the episode's liberal visual and verbal innuendo about the titular biker group being lesbians. In the segment, the Buffalo Gals break into people's homes to chew on the carpet, a biker named Munch Kelly has a carpet swatch for a calling card, and when Dad freaks out over the Buffalo Gals in the house, Mom says, \"They're not after you.\"<ref name=\"buffalo1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_18672_the-6-creepiest-things-ever-slipped-into-childrens-cartoons.html|title=The 6 Creepiest Things Ever Slipped Into Children's Cartoons|author=Anthony Scibelli|date=August 6, 2010|publisher=[[Cracked (magazine)|Cracked]]|access-date=January 16, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511114141/http://www.cracked.com/article_18672_the-6-creepiest-things-ever-slipped-into-childrens-cartoons.html|archive-date=May 11, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the Buffalo Gals play softball and talk about pitching and catching. Although it was only shown on air once, it was replaced by \"Orthodontic Police\" in future airings, including on [[Netflix]] streaming and reruns on [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]]. The episode was also discussed on an installment of [[Rob Paulsen]]'s ''Talkin' Toons'' special featuring ''Cow and Chicken'' creator David Feiss and voice actor [[Charlie Adler]] when an audience member asked why \"Buffalo Gals\" only aired once.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee(s) !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1996 || [[Annie Award]] || [[Annie Award for Best Animated Short Subject|Best Animated Short Subject]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=24th Annie Award Winners Announced|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.9/articles/news1.9.html|date=December 1996|issue=9|journal=Animation World Magazine|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|volume=1|access-date=2013-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131083922/http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.9/articles/news1.9.html|archive-date=2013-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Hanna-Barbera]]<br />{{small|for \"No Smoking\"}} || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]] || [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming One Hour or Less)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/cow-and-chicken-no-smoking|title=Cow And Chicken in No Smoking|work=[[Emmys.com]]|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|access-date=2013-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728013813/http://www.emmys.com/shows/cow-and-chicken-no-smoking|archive-date=2014-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref> || [[Buzz Potamkin]], [[Larry Huber]], [[David Feiss]], Pilar Menendez, and Sam Kieth<br />{{small|for \"No Smoking\"}} || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997 || rowspan=\"4\"|[[Annie Award]] || Best Individual Achievement: Storyboarding in a TV Production<ref>{{cite web|title=25th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (1997)|url=http://annieawards.org/25th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=[[ASIFA-Hollywood]]|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230210843/http://annieawards.org/25th-annie-awards|archive-date=2015-12-30|url-status=live}}</ref> || Nora Johnson<br />{{small|for \"Orthodontic Police\"}} || {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"|1998 || Outstanding Individual Achievement for Music in an Animated Television Production<ref name=\"a98\">{{cite web|title=26th Annual Annie Award Nominees and Winners (1998)|url=http://annieawards.org/26th-annie-awards|work=AnnieAwards.org|publisher=ASIFA-Hollywood|access-date=2013-01-26|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130223120846/http://annieawards.